{{Infobox Government agency |agency_name = Panel on Takeovers and Mergers |nativename_r = |logo = |logo_width = |logo_caption = |seal = |seal_width = |seal_caption = |formed = 1968 |preceding1 = |dissolved = |superseding = |jurisdiction = [[United Kingdom]] |headquarters = [[London]], {{postcode|EC|4}} |employees = 26 |budget = |minister1_name = |minister1_pfo = |minister2_name = |minister2_pfo = |chief1_name = Robert AJ Gillespie |chief1_position = Evercore Partners – Director General |chief2_name = |chief2_position = |parent_agency = |child1_agency = |keydocument1 = |keydocument2 = |website = http://www.thetakeoverpanel.org.uk/ |footnotes = }} {{update|date=November 2010}}
The '''Panel on Takeovers and Mergers''' (the '''Takeover Panel''' or '''PTM''') is a regulatory body located in [[London]], [[England]]. It was set up in 1968 and is charged with the administration of the [[City Code on Takeovers and Mergers]]. Its role is to ensure that all [[shareholder]]s are treated equally during takeover bids. Its main functions are to issue and administer the City Code on Takeovers and Mergers (the "Code") and to supervise and regulate takeovers and other matters to which the Code applies. Its central objective is to ensure fair treatment for all shareholders in takeover bids.
== Powers ==
The Panel is a statutory body under Chapter 1 of Part 28 (sections 942 to 965) of the Companies Act 2006 as amended by The Companies Act 2006 (Amendment of Schedule 2)(No 2) Order 2009. It has established a reputation for giving informed advice in an expert area of regulatory activity. It is the ''de facto'' arbiter of takeover bids and has the support of government and other organisations with statutory involvement.
The European Takeovers Directive mandates that the Panel is put on a statutory footing. This was completed in the [[Companies Act 2006]].<ref>[http://europa.eu/eur-lex/pri/en/oj/dat/2004/l_142/l_14220040430en00120023.pdf European Takeovers Directive]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
Whenever a transaction is made on the [[London Stock Exchange|LSE]] or other London-based [[Stock exchange|exchange]] that is greater than £10,000, the details of the transaction are passed on to the panel for their evaluation, and a levy is charged of (currently) £1.00 on the transaction, which goes to the panel as payment (known as the "PTM levy").<ref>[http://www.londonstockexchange.com/traders-and-brokers/rules-regulations/change-and-updates/stock-exchange-notices/2007/notification-ptmlevy.pdf PTM Levy - London Stock Exchange]</ref>
It was decided in ''[[R v Panel on Take-overs and Mergers, ex p Datafin plc]]'' that decisions of this panel are subject to judicial review, even though it is only a private body. This was due to its "enormous power" and "giant's strength".<ref>{{cite court |litigants= R v Panel on Take-overs and Mergers, ex parte Datafin plc|vol= &#91;1986&#93;|reporter= AppLR|opinion= 12/05|pinpoint= |court= CA|date= 5 December 1986|url= http://www.nadr.co.uk/articles/published/ArbitrationOlderReports/Data%20Fin%201986.pdf|accessdate= |quote=}}</ref> As The Panel is now a statutory footing, its decisions can now be reviewed even without referring to this case.
